<br>
First of all, when I arrived to help, I was VERY confused on who the Raid Leader was.  IMHO, the leader needs to be confident, in control, and above all, have as much knowledge as possible about the zone to be raided.  If that person is lacking in knowledge, that person needs to be willing to accept info and help from others that may save the raid, or at least save someone's butt.<br>
<br>
Second.  If you came for planar armor and/or epic drops:  don't expect to get them.  Don't ask if the mobs that drop these items will be pulled soon.  Don't ask if they are up.  Don't worry about anything farther away than listening for the puller to say &quot;INC&quot; or the MA to say &quot;assist&quot;.  Period.  End of Story.  If your mob gets pulled, be thankful.  If the item drops, be surprised.  If you get it, be elated.<br>
<br>
Third.  The break.  Sometimes the break goes surprisingly well.  More often than not, the break will take AT LEAST an hour.  Sometimes considerably longer.  I've heard varying numbers, but there are somewhere around 20 mobs to take out near the zone in.  They tend to come to the break group in 3's and 4's, all the while chatting to the rest of the zone on their cellphone about this great party in the SW corner of the zone.  Chain aggro can and will wipe a break in group.  In case you have not seen it in action, it's a lot like getting adds when a creature gets pulled - except that anything in aggro range of the add also can aggro.  And anything in range of the add's add can also aggro.  I have seen and heard about large chunks of the zone being pulled by accident because someone sat down at the break in camp.<br>
To sum it up, the break in takes time.  And the more people get antsy while waiting for the break to get done, the more spam I see in the raid channel.  Bring a book, talk to group members, let your pets duel, whatever.  Just don't be a burden to the break group - or the RL while he's trying to make sure that he doesn't have to call for a rescue party because 40+ people just died .<br>
<br>
Third.  If you have a suggestion for the RL, /tell the RL.  Or your group leader.  Don't announce it in a raid channel.  This leads to confusion, and more deaths.  If you are the RL, take all the help you can get.  But don't let someone else take control, unless you are willing to hand over that control.<br>
<br>
A couple of suggestions I have for future Fear raids:<br>
1) try and get a group of level 60+ to be the break in group, and if possible, have them in zone at or before the meeting time.  This will not often be possible, I guess its sort of a pipe dream.  But they will have a smaller aggro range because of their level, and should have a evac'er to save on deaths.  Its more important to get them out safely and whole than to take on more than they can handle.  If they can get about the first 10 mobs, another group should be able to come in to help, and shortly after that, the rest of the raid.  Works in theory, anyway.<br>
2) Farr did this, and it ended up working pretty well:  Figure out how many groups you will have, and start assigning people to be group leaders.  I think on the last couple of Fear raids he did this, we met at 8ish, and had most at the first camp by 9:30ish, so it definitely saves time.<br>
3) I think this has been pointed out many times before (as with the rest of this post...), but FEIGN DEATH DOES NOT WIPE AGGRO IN FEAR.  If you FD because of aggro, do not stand back up until you have either camped out, or you have watched every creature that had aggroed you die.  the biggest reason for this (other than wiping the camp is bad) is that the Amy you aggroed may have decided to wander.  Up towards... say... the castle.  As he's running back to pound you, since you stood back up, he has a good chance of bringing with him everything he passes by on his way.  Imagine being that RL when some monk stands up to loot his corpse after feigning his way to camp.  And about 45 seconds after he stands, about 30 mobs run into camp, including at least one mini.  I know I would have to seriously strain myself to not dump that person from the raid, put him on ignore, and completely abandon him.<br>
4)  If you do not have an assist button already made by the time you get high enough to go on a planes raid, you prolly do not need to go.<br>
<br>
Ok, I think I've rambled enough.  You will always have mistakes on a raid.  It will always be someone's first raid, and there will always be someone who doesn't know anything about the zone.  What I'm trying to do here (along with everyone else that has made a post like this - and there are a LOT) is point out that if we can do everything possible to make sure the mistakes are small.  The best raid to Fear I've ever been on was with KCoG.  As well as the worst.  The only real differences between those two raids was the cooperation, knowledge and tactics.  It is up to each individual to make the next raid better than the last. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bcouncilofguilds.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ffejdoowsk>ffejdoowsk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#8E9173>(7/18/03 12:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=350.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Why Fear Didnt go as well</span><hr size=1> <br>
I think we were able to get back on our feet and have a decent first attempt at Fear. What we need to do for next time:<br>
<br>
Break In:  Get a good game plan.  There are NUMEROUS ways of breaking in Fear and we just need to figure out which is best for us.  There is NO ONE WAY to do the break in.  I think it depends on the groups experience.<br>
<br>
Here are some suggestions:<br>
<br>
1.  NIGHT BEFORE:  Find out who has Fear the night before us and when they actually started.  This way you have a timer on the repops.  Zone in the night before to the wall and camp out.  This method only works good if you can get one high level or two group to do it.  Its is the safest way to break in Fear.  Everyone who camps out plays alts till the raid is suppost to start or goes to a chat channel to know when to log in.  Once this group has cleared the 12 mobs (There are 12 mobs that roam near the portal), then the rest zone in.  <br>
<br>
2.  Camp Out Theory:  We did this alot on the Rathe and it worked well.  Send in each group 10 secs apart.  The entire goal of the break in is to camp out as many people as possible.  The first group trys to kill as many mobs as possible and keep the mobs engaged.  You want to get a cleric camped out so they can do the rez.  You log out to a chat channel or alt and then when told to do so you camp back in.  One person must FD to keep an eye on the camp to tell when its clear to camp back in. <br>
<br>
3.  Full Charge Theory:  Man idea here is to try to kill the mobs in camp.  Send in the main group then the other groups 10 sec apart.  The key here is not to agro additional mobs.<br>
<br>
Also, I think we need to make sure everyone knows and more suggestions:<br>
<br>
1.  THESE MOBS CAN FEAR AND SUMMON.  If you get sent out of camp, DONT COME BACK.  Just died right there.  The worst thing you can do is bring more mobs into camp.  I watched one person last raid run around and bring 4 more mobs into camp.  <br>
<br>
2.  IF YOU GET LOST OR TURNED AROUND ON ZONE IN.  Dont come to camp!  Just die where you are.  Thats what coffins and summon corpse is for.  The worst thing you can do is bring more mobs into camp.<br>
<br>
3.  CALL OUT THE MAIN ASSIST AND DONT CHANGE IT.  Everyone needs to know from the start who the main assist is and to set up a key.  This should be done before the first group enters Fear.<br>
<br>
4.  ASSIGN SOMEONE TO CALL OUT LOOT.  Its a fact of life, folks get excited in Fear and thats part of the fun.  To cut down on the spam, someone should assigned the task of calling out the loot for each and every mobs.  This keeps folks happy.  Let folks know that loot WILL ONLY BE CALLED OUT after battles.  Have the person in charge of assigning the loot also in charge of handing it out in a random/fair manner.<br>
<br>
5.  START THE RAID ON TIME.  Fear raids can last up to 6 hours or more.  I would suggest starting the raid at a time that keeps that in mind.  Nothing is worse than the raid losing steam and folks gating out.  If the raid is suppost to start at 7:00 then tell folks to be there at 6:00 to get ready.  It helps the flow if the first group is going into Fear right at the start time.  <br>
<br>
6.  GET FOLKS COMMITTED AHEAD OF TIME.  It helps to know that you will have X number of clerics, X number of chanters, etc. coming to the raid and how long they can stay.  <br>
<br>
7.  ONLY EXPERIENCE IN FEAR WILL IMPROVE HOW FEAR GOES.  I would perhaps suggest that the first timers are put into a group and only zone in after the portal and surrounding area is clear.  This would be for their own safety and the raid. Then they can be put into other groups.  Mixing first timers with experiened players also helps to keep them out of trouble.  <br>
<br>
This last raid was a BIG SUCCESS because it was a learning experience.  Sure we made some mistakes but we learned from them.  The leader did the best job they could and should be saluted for taking on such a role.  <br>
<br>
We will get FEAR next time!  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bcouncilofguilds.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ebzent>Ebzent</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#8E9173>(7/18/03 2:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=350.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why Fear Didnt go as well</span><hr size=1> I agree with pretty much everything you said, ffejdoow, but for KCoG the hardest part of Fear has always been the break.  I will happily admit there are many ways to do this (including one of the more interesting ones I've heard, have 5-6 people zone in and try to pull as much as possible to the portal, where a bunch of casters basically AE everything to death).<br>
<br>
But in my experience, every single time KCoG has done well in Fear, it was because we've had a solid break in group.  In some cases 2 groups.  Not the whole raid force, not even close.<br>
<br>
The tactics are simple:  Kill anything that comes near you, until someone gets below 40% health.  Evac.  Go back in and do it again.  Once the break in group is having to start to pull, instead of waiting for a wanderer, the other groups start coming in.<br>
<br>
And again, not to point fingers, EVERY SINGLE KCoG fear raid I have been on has had people:<br>
FD &amp; stand without clearing aggro.<br>
attack mezzed mobs.<br>
Dot mezzed mobs.<br>
Not use assist.<br>
Not know who the MA/SA was.<br>
Sit in camp before it is safe.<br>
etc. etc. etc.<br>
<br>
Introducing some of the break tactics you mention IMHO is asking for trouble.  They require teamwork, trust, and familiarity, which is hard to put together in a somewhat &quot;pick-up&quot; environment.  While sign up posts are helpful, things do change, and people get added and subtracted from the raid even an hour after the meeting time.<br>
<br>
I'm not going to say that any or all of these tactics should not be tried.  I'm just saying that it will take some practice as a (large) group, and practicing on one of our few chances at Fear may not be the best way to go.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, there are other zones in the game where these tactics could be tried, and they don't have rotations.  If someone is willing to step up, Fear raids could me a lot more interesting, if nothing else. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bcouncilofguilds.showUserPublicProfile?gid=morrlokk>Morrlokk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#8E9173>(7/18/03 3:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=350.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Suggestion</span><hr size=1> Why don't we have people list the times they have been on a certain raid (Fear, Hate etc...) Same thing goes for Dragons. That way the RL has kind of an idea who has been before and who has not. That way the GL can set up groups accordingly. Now I know there are a lot of people who show up for these raids without signing up but at least the GL can get a general idea on the majority of the people that have signed up. Just a suggestion &lt;shrug&gt; <br>
