<br>
We used the single group break in method.  The key here is that you probably have groups 1-3 that are capable of doing the break so the idea is that you don't throw all your cards on the table at once, play one at a time.<br>
<br>
1 - Build 3 good strong balanced, potentially independant, groups with highest level people in group 1.  Hopefully all 55+, basically this is Kommisar's first strategy, the 55+ break.<br>
<br>
2 - Invite enough other trusted people to be group leaders to get the rest of the LFG people into groups.  Leave them to their own devices during the break to make groups.<br>
<br>
3 - Send in some FDers (like ebby here <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) to scope out the west wall camp.<br>
<br>
4 - When the FD scrouts say that things are as clear as they can be, the first group goes in invisable.  Turn left, head to camp being VERY aware of any aggro that they have.  <br>
<br>
5 - Start clearing, if this group manages to kill 4-5 mobs before having to evac then they did GREAT!  Point here is to evac before you start loosing key people. <br>
<br>
6 - After evac Group 1 gathers again outside the portal, replacing anyone who died with people pulled from farther into the raid.<br>
<br>
7 - Repeat steps 4 &amp; 5 untill you have cleared or have things very well under control and the portal is clear.  If things look safe then you can bring in group 2 to speed up clearing the immediate area.  Again, each group 2 person on zoning in, swivel around to check for aggro, then walk carefully to camp, checking behind you for a train.  If things get out of control then you will have to evac again and go back to step 4.<br>
<br>
8 - Once the portal, the camp and all nearby wanderers are dead then you can bring in the rest of the people.  The reason to wait this long is that it keeps the lower level (MUCH higher aggro radius) people out of the zone untill the area is cleared.  Also, every person you have sitting outside the zone is a potential addition to the Next break group if the one before wipes out - basically they are insurance.<br>
<br>
9 - Everyone is now in camp, get a pull team working and get those mobs killed fast.  Clear all the wanderers and work towards any minis that you want to kill.<br>
<br>
A couple of points:<br>
<br>
Clearing Plane of Fear is generally done in a fairly methodical manner.  Pull everything you can to that first camp, this includes the whole west wall (not too far north if CT is up though) and about half of the south wall.  Then you move the camp along the south wall clearing the south side.  From the south wall you pull up the middle... again this all depends on what minis are up.<br>
<br>
Mobs are pulled in an order that is dictated by the LARGER strategy of clearing the whole plane and minis asap.  The puller is not picking and choosing which mobs to pull, they are clearing areas.  Asking the puller or raid leader to pull something specific NOW is foolish because they already have a larger order in mind and they will NOT be changing their mind on the order of things.  Pulling in PoFear takes 110% of the pullers concentration.  If you annoy the puller with requests then they are just as likely to pass up pulling your mob given the choice!  However as I said, the puller really doesn't have any choice - they are told by the raid leader to Pull an area clean, they will be taking the easiest and closest pulls first and nothing will be missed.<br>
<br>
Using a Pally for tanking here is a good idea because you won't be very successfull in getting people to wait for a warrior to get aggro.  With a Paladin tank and pally snap aggro abilities, as soon as the tank is swinging, everyone can attack.  This means faster clearing time.  I will admit a small conflict of interrest here :P<br>
<br>
Having people who have done PoFear before be your group leaders and have them reassuring the troops that yes.. it is supposed to go like this etc is a good idea.  <br>
<br>
One of the reason that Farr was so successfull in fear is that we were able to provide from SOTV and IoS our alliance a set of group leaders that had for the most part done lots of KCOG planar raids in the past, seen the good, the bad, and the ugly.  He also didn't take any crap from anybody.<br>
<br>
All that said, any PoFear raid where you got the plane broken and got some progress done was a good raid.  Seriously, if you aren't doing CR till 4AM it was a good night, regardless if you left a couple of minis up or wiped a few times, that happens.<br>
<br>
The no sitting thing is important, particularly before the camp area is 100% secure.  Nuff said.<br>
<br>
Pets - Pet control is a MUST here.  You must activly be aware of the location of your pet at all times.  The little imp guys proc a shadowstep on the main tank which throws him away from the camp, then the mob leaves the camp looking for the tank.  If pets chase him when he does this and then manage to get aggro on him then the tank won't be able to drag the mob back to camp and the pet will be out in the middle of nowhere soloing the mob... and it's friends... which become our friends when the pet dies.  If your pet is misbehaving you will be asked to kill it.  Do so immediatly and once you are ready to pay closer attention, you can have another one.  If the RL shouts &quot;Kill the air pet&quot; then kill it because it is probably out of your sight doing something it shouldn't be.  <br>
<br>
While things are still hairy in the main camp, the raid leader may choose to not allow pets at all.  This is not an insult to you personally.  Yes, he is probably aware of how pet aggro works nowadays.  The RL is also well aware that of all the pet classes on the raid, someone is probably a little tired tonight and not 100% on their game and so untill things are secure, they may not want pets around.<br>
<br>
Earth Pets = rooting pets = very very bad.  Root aggro rules are that the mob attacks the closest toon, not the main tank.  This means the mob is nearly untankable, dont do this please!  No earth pets allowed.<br>
<br>
Low Level Pets - There should be no low level pets in Fear ever.  Druid and SK pets fall into thie category - they are cute but they do insignificant DPS and while pets don't aggro when not aggressive, a level 30 boo boo bear attacking for 2 dps has a HUGE aggro radius and a mob that would otherwize have walked right on past will instead charge in.<br>
<br>
Nuff said for now :P<br>
