<br>
But from what I've seen, and heard, over the last few weeks have led me to believe that was not really the best move.<br>
<br>
Anyway.  To address a few points here.<br>
<br>
You may not enter Fear early.  I will not hesitate to hand out a penalty to KCoG for breaking this rule.  Period.  The only way you may enter the plane early is if they allow you.  It doesnt even matter if that guild is no longer IN the plane.  It belongs to them and them alone until 12AM KCoG local time.  And then only if the other guild has left.  The guild up has until 3am EST to clear out.<br>
<br>
Okay, thats the rules crap out of the way.  Here's the main of it all.<br>
<br>
The Break-In.<br>
<br>
Preliminary break.  When I was running KCoG Planar raids I used 3 Break Groups max.  It didnt matter if I had 80+ people, only the 3 break groups went in until things were clear.<br>
<br>
Why?<br>
<br>
Simple.  Its far easier to control 3 groups than 12 on the fly with the crap flying.  Fear breaks have the potential with aggro and pathing issues to be one of the hardest in the game when it goes wrong.  Limiting yourself to only 3 groups is one of the easier ways to control that.<br>
<br>
Second, its far easier to find 2 other good group leaders than 12.  Just as its easier to find 18 good people than 80.<br>
<br>
Third.  Possibly the most important depending on how pessimistic you are, 3 groups max means that even if it goes to hell, you still have as many as 10 more groups ready to make a go at it before you need to call in the CR teams.<br>
<br>
So...3 groups.  Is the makeup important?  Or can I just slap together a bunch of tanks and healers?<br>
<br>
Absolutely.  The number 1 job of the Raid Leader at this stage is group makeup.  You screw this up, and you can kiss your raid goodbye.  No matter how many level 65's you have.  I've seen few things more sad in my life than 2 groups of Nightbane with 12 level 65's with 2 sets of warriors, clerics, and enchanters, along with their support get wiped trying to break Fear.  If they could screw it up, anyone can.<br>
<br>
My basic group setup was as follows for the break:<br>
<br>
Group 1 - AKA The Command Group<br>
<br>
Slot 1: Puller (FD capable)<br>
Slot 2: Tank (3rd most capable tank available)<br>
Slot 3: Healer type<br>
Slot 4: Enchanter/bard (your mezzer goes here)<br>
Slot 5: Random DPS class. (wizard preferable)<br>
Slot 6: Me (if you are not an evac class, than slot 5 must be an evac'r)<br>
<br>
Group 2 - AKA Main Assist Group<br>
<br>
Slot 1: Your Main Assist (Best tank available)<br>
Slot 2: Your Main Healer (Best healer available...usually a cleroc)<br>
Slot 3: Paladin<br>
Slot 4: Evac'r<br>
Slot 5: Shaman<br>
Slot 6: Random DPS class<br>
<br>
Group 3 - AKA Secondary Assist Group<br>
<br>
Slot 1: Your Secondary Assist Tank (2nd Best tank available)<br>
Slot 2: Your Second Best Healer<br>
Slot 3: Paladin<br>
Slot 4: Evac'r<br>
Slot 5: Random DPS class<br>
Slot 6: Random DPS class<br>
<br>
I always made sure my Raid Second (You know, that guy who will make all the raid calls like evac) is in Group 3 somewhere.<br>
<br>
You will note, none of the 3 groups are really perfect.  But they are geared towards one thing.  Mutual support.  You will also note there is only 1 enchanter here.  Resist the temptation to include multiple enchanters.  Unless they are used to working with each other, they will probably just get in each other's way and end up killing the other one.  Also, in case it goes to hell, you'll want a fully clothed enchanter in reserve.  Always keep an eye on your tactical reserves.<br>
<br>
Strategy<br>
<br>
Wait...this is a break.  Isnt it just go in and kill?<br>
<br>
After going through all that trouble of making the groups, nope.<br>
<br>
Okay.  So first off, get SoE or lev on everyone in the break groups.  Second, invis them all.  Yes, mobs at the portal see invis, but invis does lower aggro radius, and more important, some of the mobs at the portal DONT see inivis.  Half of a cake is better than none.<br>
<br>
Make sure your people know what they're doing.  Make sure they understand that once they enter Fear they are to turn LEFT and run to West Camp.  That they are NOT to move forward.  Not a single step.  They are to stand there, use the arrow key to turn LEFT and then move.  Or wait till they can.  Moving even a single step forward or to the right can cause aggro from a different direction if you are unlucky.  And the risk only increases as you move more.<br>
<br>
I cannot stress how often I see wipes because of this.  Never, ever, ever move forward or to the right on a Fear break.  Ever.  Burn this into your mind.  If this is the only thing you take away from this post, that needs to be it.<br>
<br>
So, you are going LEFT to west camp.  Bring your mobs.  Yes, dont stop.  Dont die.  BRING them all.<br>
<br>
Now here you have 2 different strategies.<br>
<br>
Typical Break.  Once you are in West camp you should have some mobs in camp.  1 or 10 it doesnt really matter.  Believe me, so long as your enchanter is halfway decent and does more on a daily basis than whore KEI or C2 in PoK they will be able to control up to 6-8 mobs at once.  I've seen the best keep close to 16 mobs mez'd and charmed and controlled at once in Fear.<br>
<br>
Then have your MA and SA pick their own seperate targets and engage.  Only use this method if you have many mobs in camp.  Otherwise, have everyone assist the MA.<br>
<br>
Whatever you do here.  Always use assist.  And be prepared to expel the first non-MA/SA person to break mez from the raid permenently.<br>
<br>
As long as your enchanter is alive, you can and probably will live.  As soon as your enchanter goes down, its time to evac.  Bottom line.  In this type of Fear break, no class is more important to success than your enchanter.  Break mez and get banned from KCoG raids along with your guild if necessary.  You need to be firm here, otherwise you might as well stay at home.<br>
<br>
In this break you want to always be prepared to evac to South Ro.  Here druids are better evacer's than wizards.  But remember, if you use a druid to evac, they cannot be a healer or nuker at the same time.  They must remain invis'd at all times till the break is over.<br>
<br>
Calling the evac is a tough call.  You want to kill as many wanderers as possible before evacing, but you dont want to lose anyone if possible.  Done right you shouldnt ever have to evac, but if you do, its an easy run back.  Do this 2 or 3 times right and you'll have cleared the wanderers easily.<br>
<br>
AE Break.  You can use the same group makeup (or slightly different one) to do an AE break.  This requires the Enchanter to chain stun.  And it would be preferable to have 2 enchanters.<br>
<br>
I'm not a fan of the AE break as most KCoG raids dont have an abundance of enchanters.  I feel its better to do a typical melee break and leave your spare enchanter(s) in reserve in case of a bad break.  AE breaks can be fun, and can clear the zone in an hour or two.  But they can also be very dangerous unless your people are used to working with each other.<br>
<br>
I've done both with KCoG raids, and I can say I prefer the melee breaks.<br>
<br>
Now here's the main thing.  Experience.  You want to have your most experienced people in those 3 break groups.   Those will remain your main groups throughout the raid.  Please note who and where I placed people in each group.  That was not by accident.<br>
<br>
You want your puller in the same group as the enchanter so they can easily coordinate.  Sure, there are /raid channels and normal channels, but nothing beats the simplicity of group chat, and you wont have the rest of the raid hearing this communication.  The last thing you want are people complaining because they know ahead of time the mob they want isnt coming right now.  <br>
<br>
Also, keeping the enchanter out of a melee group means your healer only has to keep an eye on the enchanter realistically.  The tank is not there in the group to fight, but rather to shield the enchanter and taunt the mob off him/her.  I would fully expect the tank to fight to the end here and die while the healer heals the enchanter and ignores the dying tank.  Their job is not to live or win or do damage, but to protect the enchanter.<br>
<br>
Also, you want your raid commander to be in the group with the puller and enchanter so he/she can more easily keep an eye on whats going on.  You'll note he/she too is not in the MA group.  This is because the last thing the raid leader needs to do is be distracted by combat.  They need to keep a close eye out on the general situation.  As a raid leader, distance yourself from combat as much as possible.  It is true you need to lead from the front, but also remember a dead leader is a useless leader.  And a confused one is even worse.<br>
<br>
As a Raid Leader always do your best to avoid any sort of combat role for yourself.  Its not as fun or glamorous, but the bottom line is that you are responsible for the success of the raid.  A Raid Leader cannot be distracted by anything unecessary.  They need to be watching the action and calculating the risks of staying vs doing something different.  The line between successfully breaking Fear and living wiht only 1 or 2 people left, or totally wiping out is very slim and you need to know which is which.<br>
<br>
Oh, and here's another important TIP.  Since you went through the trouble of putting experienced people in your 3 break groups...LET THEM DO THEIR JOB.<br>
<br>
I can count the number of times I've overruled my MA or Enchanter or puller on one hand with 4 fingers left over.  You put them in good positions, let them make the calls.  Have your type commanders call their shots and you'll have lifted half the burden off you.<br>
<br>
So to recap:<br>
<br>
3 groups max to break.<br>
<br>
Make sure its your best people.  And try to follow the group layout when possible.  Changes must be made here and there, but in general this is one of the best multicapable setup's I've come up with for KCoG raids.<br>
<br>
Make sure you are invis'd and everyone knows to turn LEFT.<br>
<br>
Keep your evac'r invis'd at all times during the break.  The evacer is not ever supposed to break invis for any reason or do anything to draw aggro for any reason till the break is done.  Nothing will screw your chances of a good clean break faster than losing your enchanter followed by that nuking wizard/druid and now losing 1-3 groups instead of just 1 or 2 people.<br>
<br>
Melee vs AE break.  Its up to you.  But unless you are positive you can do it, and have done it before, and your people are good...I'd suggest a melee break for KCoG.  It might not seem as sexy, but its far safer generally.<br>
<br>
Keep control and discipline in your raid.  If you are the raid commander it is your paramont job to keep control.  You need to be on top of all channels and be ready to boot people if necessary.  You'll note the raid commander is not even needed in the Command Group for any real combat potential.  As the group evacer I usually just stood around and watched and made sure things went according to plan.  I never engaged in combat and only occasionally healed on my raids.<br>
<br>
Delegate combat responsibilities to your type commanders and let them do their job.  If you cant trust them to do it, you have no business going into the plane in the first place.<br>
<br>
Experience is always better than levels.  Good people over levels will always win out.  I've had a level 60 ranger MA'ing in Fear over a 60 epic equiped warrior because the Ranger was far more reliable in his judgement.<br>
<br>
Will this guarantee a successful raid?  Of course not.  But I'll tell you this, my Fear raids rarely ran over 4 hours.  Often they were only about 3.  And we generally cleared most of the plane.  And this was almost 2 years ago now.  KCoG shouldnt have any problems today the way equipment, levels, and spells have changed.<br>
<br>
To put things in perspective.<br>
<br>
My guild, The Watchmen, usually only fields about 8-12 people for a Fear raid.  We will break, clean, and are done with all mobs and mini's in Fear within 3 hours of start time.  This is with no one over 63 really, and only 1 enchanter and occasionally no clerics.<br>
<br>
And this is using a melee approch.  If we wanted to AE (as we sometimes need to if we have something else scheduled that night) we will AE and be done in an hour or so.<br>
<br>
Many other guilds can do Fear in similar or better times with as many people.<br>
<br>
KCoG should have no problems with the numbers they can field today.<br>
<br>
The one thing I disagree with Rhedd about is using a paladin to tank.  He's right about their abilities and its good.  But if aggro is an issue because people are not waiting for the assist call, then they need to get punted from the raid and banned from KCoG raids.<br>
<br>
The one thing I always stressed was raid discipline.  And continue to do so.  Failue to abide by assists or wait for them has always been grounds for immediate dismissal from my guild.  Its a rare thing, we usually handle that sort of thing with a few private talks, but we have been known to expell people from the guild in the middle of a raid because of that.<br>
<br>
/assist is a raider's most impotant tool.  Use it or be it.<br>
<br>
Beyond that, for the average raider my only advice is this:<br>
<br>
Shut Up and Listen.<br>
<br>
Bottom line.  Your job as a raider is to do whatever job the Raid Leader has told you to do.  Period.  Even if you dont agree or think its stupid or dont want to do it.  Either do it without question, or go home.<br>
<br>
For you Raid Leaders or Potential Raid Leaders, all I can do is quote my Sensei.<br>
<br>
With Rank Comes Responsibility.  The More Rank, The More Responsibility.<br>
<br>
Remember that.  Its not your job to remind people of how good you are, or how well you can crit, or anything else.  Its your job to make sure you win with the least amount of casualties.  And dont be afraid to wield a large club.  Do not be afraid to punt people if they are not listening to you.<br>
<br>
Everyone is new once.  Everyone makes mistakes.  No one should be allowed to continue making the same mistakes and jeapordising an entire raid though.<br>
<br>
Be fair, but firm.<br>
<br>
Okay, this has gone on too long, and I'd be surprised if people made it down this far.  Pat yourself on the back if you did.<br>
<br>
You know...I also forgot the most important thing here.<br>
<br>
Have Fun.<br>
